The paper deals with the prophet inequality problem and its generalizations to matroids and combinatorial auctions, which are central topics in game theory and mechanism design. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.GT (Computer Science - Game Theory and Economics). The paper also involves threshold-based techniques and dynamic adjustments, which are common in algorithms and data structures, suggesting that cs.DS (Computer Science - Data Structures and Algorithms) is another likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of random arrival models and optimization of expected total welfare, which are relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper involves mathematical analysis and optimization, which are relevant to information theory (cs.IT).
